# Slipway Workflow

```
IRON LAW: THIS SKILL ROUTES INTO THE CLI; IT DOES NOT REPLACE THE CLI
```

## Purpose
Use `{{.PublicName}}` as the single exported entry skill for Slipway. It tells
an AI how to enter governed work correctly, how to continue an active change,
when to read governed host skills, and when to consult catalog or technique
skills.

Slipway is a governance CLI for AI-assisted software delivery. A governed
change is the unit of work. The lifecycle moves through intake, plan, execute,
review, and verify. `done-ready` means the change has satisfied the workflow
gates and can be finalized; `done` happens only after explicit `slipway done`.

## When to Use
- first contact with a Slipway-enabled repository
- deciding whether a governed change already exists
- deciding between `status`, `new`, `next`, `run`, and `done`
- needing to understand which Slipway skill class should own the next step
- needing the outbound catalog manifest or governed host handoff path

## When NOT to Use
- `slipway next --json` already returned a governed host: switch to `next_skill.prompt_path`
- catalog triage is already the task: read `{{.CatalogManifestPath}}`
- a technique skill is already the right posture overlay: use that technique skill directly
- detailed per-command contract review is needed: read `references/command-reference.md`

## Intent Classification at Entry
When starting governed work and you can classify intent directly, enter through
`slipway new --json`.

Provide these fields when known:
- `guardrail_domain`: sensitive-domain classification for the change itself
- `complexity`: `trivial`, `simple`, `complex`, or `critical`
- `needs_discovery`: `true` when the scope or codebase still needs investigation

If these fields are omitted, the CLI applies conservative fallback defaults.

## Skill Taxonomy
- governance skills: runtime-selected hosts for the current workflow state
- catalog skills: outbound work-skill catalog referenced by manifest
- technique skills: posture/procedure overlays, not lifecycle authorities
- standalone skills: exported helpers such as this workflow entry skill

## Runtime Authority Boundaries
- `ResolveNextSkill` selects governed host skills. This skill does not guess or override that selection.
- `commandRegistry` owns command descriptions, arguments, prerequisites, and surface metadata.
- `using-slipway-catalog.md` is outbound only. It helps the AI triage catalog skills; the kernel does not read it back.
- existing CLI commands remain the only execution surface. This skill never reimplements transitions, gates, or command semantics.

## Primary Route Table

| Situation | Command |
|---|---|
| Unsure whether a governed change already exists | `slipway status --json` |
| No active change and governed work should begin | `slipway new --json` |
| Active change and you need the next governed host without advancing | `slipway next --json` |
| Active change and you want the CLI to advance to the next governed step | `slipway run --json` |
| The change is already `done-ready` and should be finalized | `slipway done` |

After `slipway next --json`:
- read `next_skill.prompt_path`
- use `next_skill.agent_hint` when dispatch guidance is present
- use `next_skill.agent_definition_path` when an adapter-visible agent definition is present
- do not guess the next governed host without the CLI response

## Detailed Contract Delegation
The concise summary stays here. Detailed command contracts live in
`references/command-reference.md`.

For commands that ship generated command surfaces, prefer the generated command
surface over re-explaining the command inline.

{{if eq .ToolID "codex"}}For Codex, command surfaces remain global prompt files under
`~/.codex/prompts/slipway-<command>.md`.{{else}}For `{{.ToolID}}`, command surfaces live under the generated workspace command
directory `{{.CommandsDir}}`.{{end}}

CLI-only diagnostics such as `stats`, `health`, and `codebase-map` do not have
separate command prompt surfaces; use the generated workflow reference file for
their detailed arguments and prerequisites.

## Catalog and Host Handoff
- when catalog triage is needed, read `{{.CatalogManifestPath}}`
- Start with the `Triage index` and one-line `Summary`; those are the compact dispatcher
- use the catalog when no governed host already owns the next step and a reusable posture, procedure, checklist, or tool recipe would help
- once a specific catalog skill is clearly the right tool, leave this entry skill and load that catalog skill directly
- when governed execution is needed, read the host returned by `slipway next --json`
- use technique skills as overlays for posture and procedure, not as progression authorities
- once a more specific host, command surface, or catalog skill clearly owns the task, leave this entry skill and follow that more specific surface

